            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="accordion">
                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What is the difference between Energy Systems Engineering and Electrical Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Energy Systems Engineering is a broader, interdisciplinary field that integrates principles from electrical, mechanical, and chemical engineering to address energy generation, conversion, storage, and utilization across multiple sectors. While Electrical Engineering focuses primarily on electrical power systems, electronics, and electrical devices, Energy Systems Engineering takes a holistic approach to energy challenges, including renewable energy integration, energy efficiency, and sustainability considerations across the entire energy value chain.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What skills are most important for a career in Energy Systems Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Key skills for energy systems engineers include strong knowledge of thermodynamics, electrical power systems, and energy conversion principles; proficiency in energy modeling and simulation software; understanding of renewable energy technologies and grid integration; analytical problem-solving abilities; and knowledge of energy economics and policy. Additionally, interdisciplinary thinking, systems approach to problem-solving, and familiarity with sustainability concepts are valuable for career advancement in this field.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What are the emerging areas in Energy Systems Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Emerging areas include grid-scale energy storage technologies, smart grid and microgrid systems, green hydrogen production and utilization, sector coupling between electricity, heat, and transportation, energy system digitalization using AI and IoT, vehicle-to-grid integration, and advanced energy management systems. The integration of distributed energy resources and development of resilient energy systems for climate adaptation are also growing fields.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">How is the job market for Energy Systems Engineers in India?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>The job market for energy systems engineers in India is robust and growing rapidly, driven by the country's ambitious renewable energy targets (450 GW by 2030), grid modernization initiatives, and energy efficiency programs. Government policies supporting clean energy transition, increasing private sector investments in renewable energy, and international climate commitments are creating numerous opportunities. Energy systems engineers with expertise in solar and wind energy, energy storage, smart grid technologies, and energy efficiency are particularly in demand.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What certifications can enhance my employability as an Energy Systems Engineer?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Valuable certifications include Certified Energy Manager (CEM), Renewable Energy Professional (REP), LEED Accredited Professional, Certified Smart Grid Professional, Energy Storage Professional (ESP), and PMP certification for project management. Industry-specific certifications in solar PV design, wind energy, power systems, and energy auditing can also be beneficial depending on your career focus. Additionally, software certifications for energy modeling tools like HOMER, RETScreen, or power system simulation software add value to your profile.</p>
                        </div>
